This paper is about generative modeling, which is a subfield of machine learning. The paper specifically focuses on improving the stability and accuracy of Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs), which are commonly used in computer vision (cs.CV) and natural language processing (cs.CL). The paper also introduces a new formulation for generative modeling based on random projections, which could fall under information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper discusses the use of the Wasserstein distance, which is a popular metric in optimization and probability theory, suggesting that the paper could also be categorized under neural networks (cs.NE) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
